				\begin{document}$$450\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document} were chosen for further study. At low thermal exposure, a distinct worm-like pattern appears when as-deposited films are inspected in an optical microscope. This pattern disappears and a uniform film appears as temperature is increased. Hence, higher pre-annealing temperatures allow more chloride to disappear and less porosity in the annealed film. Nonetheless, the best devices were made at lower thermal exposure during pre-annealing, because the short-circuit current drops as temperature is increased. The drop in JSC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
